{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17418433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17418433"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"791"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490976"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:26:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:26:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"791"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261514"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:42+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":7,"questionsAnswered":6,"marksTotal":6,"marksAttainable":6,"marksAttempted":6,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:40+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/791"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.11,0.72,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/791"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43078"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"6400"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17902"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a painful scrotal swelling of two days duration. The pain came on gradually, and there are no other genitourinary symptoms. His medical history includes a bilateral orchidopexy for maldescent in early childhood and an appendicectomy at age 17. He recently started a new sexual relationship. On examination, the left side of the scrotum and contents feel normal, and there is a tender swelling immediately behind the right testis, which itself feels soft, smooth, 3 cm in length, and lying with its long axis in the vertical plane.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Orchitis","Seminoma","Epididymitis","Teratoma","Torsion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute scrotal pain in a young adult or adolescent should always raise the possibility of torsion of a testis. This is the first and most important diagnosis to exclude, as any delay may lead to complete loss of that testis. In most of these cases the pain is of such severity that the patient would seek early help - and not linger for two days. In this case, both testes can be felt without causing any undue pain - and that would be unusual in torsion, where the ischaemic organ can be very tender. In addition, they are in the normal anatomical position. The \u0027bell clapper\u0027 testis in a horizontal line in associated with an increased risk of torsion. Whilst the history of maldescent is a risk factor for testicular malignancy, these tumours tend to present with a mass and not pain. If the patient had orchitis, the testis would be swollen and tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe region of swelling and tenderness described in this case suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Eepididymitis\u003C/strong\u003E; the gradual onset of scrotal pain and tenderness localised to the area behind the testis is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eepididymitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The recent start of a new sexual relationship suggests a possible sexually transmitted infection, which is a common cause of epididymitis in young men.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrchitis\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with a swollen and tender testis, rather than a localised swelling behind the testis. It is often associated with systemic symptoms like fever, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeminoma\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eteratoma\u003C/strong\u003E are types of testicular cancer that usually present as a painless testicular mass rather than acute pain. The history of maldescent increases the risk of testicular cancer, but the presentation in this case is more consistent with an inflammatory process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETorsion\u003C/strong\u003E of the testis is a surgical emergency characterised by sudden onset of severe pain and a high-riding, tender testis. The gradual onset of pain and the normal position of the testis in this case make torsion less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute scrotal pain in a young adult should prompt consideration of testicular torsion, but other causes like epididymitis must also be considered.","Epididymitis often presents with gradual onset scrotal pain and tenderness localised to the epididymis, often associated with recent sexual activity."],"references":["Bourke MM, Silverberg JZ. Acute Scrotal Emergencies. Emerg Med Clin N Am 2019; 37:593-610.","Boujelbene, N., Cosinschi, A., Boujelbene, N. et al. Pure seminoma: A review and update. Radiat Oncol 6, 90 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1186/1748-717X-6-90","Rupp TJ, Leslie SW. Epididymitis. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430814/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43078"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"791"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43078"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-26T21:36:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-26T21:37:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"791"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57619"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7